</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography/computed tomography (PET/CT) is increasingly used in the initial staging, evaluation of treatment response, and surveillance of many malignancies. Uptake of FDG is substantially increased in most malignancies, compared with its uptake in normal tissues, and the finding of FDG avidity often leads to cancer detection earlier than abnormalities can be seen at anatomic imaging. However, FDG is not a cancer-specific agent, and FDG avidity can be seen in many benign processes. It can be particularly challenging to discriminate malignancy from benign FDG-avid changes caused by surgery and procedures, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy. FDG-avid abnormalities caused by surgery and procedures include inflammation at sites of incision or dissection, inflammation from vascular compromise or surgical retraction, surgical transposition of structures with physiologic FDG avidity (such as ovaries or testes), and pleurodesis inflammation. Radiation therapy may induce FDG-avid pneumonitis, esophagitis, or hepatitis, as well as osteoradionecrosis or fractures. FDG-avid chemotherapy complications include pneumonitis, osteonecrosis, enterocolitis, and pancreatitis. Use of granulocyte colony stimulating factor for treatment of bone marrow suppression after chemotherapy induces temporary increases of FDG avidity in the bone marrow and spleen. Familiarity with common and unusual iatrogenic causes of FDG avidity that can confound interpretation of FDG PET/CT results will improve the accuracy of distinguishing treatment effects and complications from residual or recurrent malignancy at FDG PET/CT examinations.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336125105">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336125105">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig01a.jpeg" height="554" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig01a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> FDG-avid postsurgical changes after lumpectomy and axillary lymph node dissection in a 60-year-old female breast cancer patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images obtained 1 month after surgery demonstrate FDG-avid soft tissue in the left lateral breast and axillary surgical beds (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Follow-up images obtained 5 months after surgery show decreased size and resolved FDG avidity in the residual soft tissue (arrowheads), findings that represent resolving postsurgical inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig01a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig01b.jpeg" height="558" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig01b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> FDG-avid postsurgical changes after lumpectomy and axillary lymph node dissection in a 60-year-old female breast cancer patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images obtained 1 month after surgery demonstrate FDG-avid soft tissue in the left lateral breast and axillary surgical beds (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Follow-up images obtained 5 months after surgery show decreased size and resolved FDG avidity in the residual soft tissue (arrowheads), findings that represent resolving postsurgical inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig01b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig02a.jpeg" height="651" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig02a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Omental infarction after intraabdominal surgery in a 49-year-old man after bowel resection for lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate an FDG-avid, mixed soft-tissue and fat-attenuation intraperitoneal lesion (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Follow-up images obtained 3 months after surgery show decreasing size and FDG avidity of the lesion, findings that represent resolving omental infarction (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig02a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig02b.jpeg" height="643" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig02b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Omental infarction after intraabdominal surgery in a 49-year-old man after bowel resection for lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate an FDG-avid, mixed soft-tissue and fat-attenuation intraperitoneal lesion (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Follow-up images obtained 3 months after surgery show decreasing size and FDG avidity of the lesion, findings that represent resolving omental infarction (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig02b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig03a.jpeg" height="585" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig03a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Injury from liver retraction during gastrectomy in a 45-year-old woman who had presented with a gastric mass. Pathologic analysis of the gastrectomy specimen demonstrated gastric lymphoma, and FDG PET/CT was ordered for staging. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images show an FDG-avid linear band of low attenuation in the left hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image depicts a corresponding linear area of increased signal intensity (arrows). The linear distribution of the abnormalities was attributed to blunt hepatic injury from a surgical retractor during recent surgery. Follow-up PET/CT and MR images obtained 2 months later (not shown) demonstrated resolution of all abnormalities.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig03a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig03b.jpeg" height="651" width="901" aria-labelledby="fig03b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Injury from liver retraction during gastrectomy in a 45-year-old woman who had presented with a gastric mass. Pathologic analysis of the gastrectomy specimen demonstrated gastric lymphoma, and FDG PET/CT was ordered for staging. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images show an FDG-avid linear band of low attenuation in the left hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image depicts a corresponding linear area of increased signal intensity (arrows). The linear distribution of the abnormalities was attributed to blunt hepatic injury from a surgical retractor during recent surgery. Follow-up PET/CT and MR images obtained 2 months later (not shown) demonstrated resolution of all abnormalities.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig03b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig04a.jpeg" height="596" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig04a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Transposed right testis in a 20-year-old man who had undergone left orchiectomy for a paratesticular rhabdomyosarcoma. FDG PET/CT was performed for planning subsequent high-dose radiation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate FDG-avid soft tissue in the right inguinal region (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images of the scrotum show not only surgical absence of the left testis, but also absence of the right testis with a non-FDG-avid residual fluid collection (arrowheads). The FDG-avid soft tissue in the right inguinal region represents the surgically transposed right testis, not a metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig04b.jpeg" height="576" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig04b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Transposed right testis in a 20-year-old man who had undergone left orchiectomy for a paratesticular rhabdomyosarcoma. FDG PET/CT was performed for planning subsequent high-dose radiation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate FDG-avid soft tissue in the right inguinal region (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images of the scrotum show not only surgical absence of the left testis, but also absence of the right testis with a non-FDG-avid residual fluid collection (arrowheads). The FDG-avid soft tissue in the right inguinal region represents the surgically transposed right testis, not a metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig05a.jpeg" height="535" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig05a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Transposed left ovary in a 28-year-old woman who had undergone extensive resection of a rectal cancer with pelvic metastases. FDG PET/CT was performed for planning subsequent high-dose radiation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate an FDG-avid focus in the left lower abdomen (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial image from a subsequent contrast material–enhanced CT examination shows a normal ovary at this location (arrow). The FDG-avid focus represents a physiologic ovarian cyst, not a metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig05a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig05b.jpeg" height="515" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig05b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Transposed left ovary in a 28-year-old woman who had undergone extensive resection of a rectal cancer with pelvic metastases. FDG PET/CT was performed for planning subsequent high-dose radiation therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate an FDG-avid focus in the left lower abdomen (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial image from a subsequent contrast material–enhanced CT examination shows a normal ovary at this location (arrow). The FDG-avid focus represents a physiologic ovarian cyst, not a metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig05b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig06a.jpeg" height="1115" width="649" aria-labelledby="fig06a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Non–FDG-avid paralyzed vocal cord that became FDG avid after injection in a 51-year-old woman with poorly differentiated thyroid cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (top) and fused PET/CT (bottom) images demonstrate FDG photopenia of the right vocal cord (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) FDG PET image shows multiple FDG-avid right-sided mediastinal nodes (arrow) that presumably compromise the right recurrent laryngeal nerve and cause right vocal cord paralysis. To bring the right vocal cord from a lateral position to a medial position and allow better phonation, the cord was injected with synthetic material. <b>(c)</b> On follow-up images obtained after injection, the paralyzed right vocal cord appears FDG avid, representing inflammation associated with the high-attenuation injected material (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig06a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig06b.jpeg" height="1115" width="591" aria-labelledby="fig06b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Non–FDG-avid paralyzed vocal cord that became FDG avid after injection in a 51-year-old woman with poorly differentiated thyroid cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (top) and fused PET/CT (bottom) images demonstrate FDG photopenia of the right vocal cord (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) FDG PET image shows multiple FDG-avid right-sided mediastinal nodes (arrow) that presumably compromise the right recurrent laryngeal nerve and cause right vocal cord paralysis. To bring the right vocal cord from a lateral position to a medial position and allow better phonation, the cord was injected with synthetic material. <b>(c)</b> On follow-up images obtained after injection, the paralyzed right vocal cord appears FDG avid, representing inflammation associated with the high-attenuation injected material (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig06b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig06c.jpeg" height="1115" width="610" aria-labelledby="fig06c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Non–FDG-avid paralyzed vocal cord that became FDG avid after injection in a 51-year-old woman with poorly differentiated thyroid cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (top) and fused PET/CT (bottom) images demonstrate FDG photopenia of the right vocal cord (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) FDG PET image shows multiple FDG-avid right-sided mediastinal nodes (arrow) that presumably compromise the right recurrent laryngeal nerve and cause right vocal cord paralysis. To bring the right vocal cord from a lateral position to a medial position and allow better phonation, the cord was injected with synthetic material. <b>(c)</b> On follow-up images obtained after injection, the paralyzed right vocal cord appears FDG avid, representing inflammation associated with the high-attenuation injected material (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig06c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig07a.jpeg" height="1020" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig07a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Pleurodesis inflammation in a 58-year-old woman who had undergone right pleurodesis for pleural effusion and whose breast cancer is in remission. MIP FDG PET image <b>(a)</b> and coronal CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images <b>(b)</b> demonstrate FDG avidity along the right pleura (arrow in <b>a</b>) that corresponds to the high-attenuation nodularity seen at CT (arrows in <b>b</b>). The patient had stable FDG-avid pleurodesis inflammation for over 2 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig07a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig07b.jpeg" height="673" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig07b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Pleurodesis inflammation in a 58-year-old woman who had undergone right pleurodesis for pleural effusion and whose breast cancer is in remission. MIP FDG PET image <b>(a)</b> and coronal CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images <b>(b)</b> demonstrate FDG avidity along the right pleura (arrow in <b>a</b>) that corresponds to the high-attenuation nodularity seen at CT (arrows in <b>b</b>). The patient had stable FDG-avid pleurodesis inflammation for over 2 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig07b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig08a.jpeg" height="544" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig08a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Radiation pneumonitis in a 35-year-old man with Ewing sarcoma who had undergone irradiation for mediastinal metastases. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images obtained before irradiation demonstrate a mediastinal mass (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On follow-up images obtained after radiation therapy, the mass has resolved. New linear FDG-avid scarring seen within the radiation port (arrows) represents radiation pneumonitis along the radiation beam.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig08a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig08b.jpeg" height="607" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig08b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Radiation pneumonitis in a 35-year-old man with Ewing sarcoma who had undergone irradiation for mediastinal metastases. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images obtained before irradiation demonstrate a mediastinal mass (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On follow-up images obtained after radiation therapy, the mass has resolved. New linear FDG-avid scarring seen within the radiation port (arrows) represents radiation pneumonitis along the radiation beam.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig08b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig09.jpeg" height="625" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig09" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Osteoradionecrosis in a 47-year-old woman with breast cancer who underwent lumpectomy and radiation therapy. Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images show an FDG-avid destructive lesion that involves the sternum (arrows). The differential diagnosis for this lesion includes metastatic breast cancer, radiation-induced sarcoma, and benign osteoradionecrosis. Biopsy was required to differentiate among these possibilities and demonstrated benign osteonecrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig09">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig10a.jpeg" height="593" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Radiation-induced sacral insufficiency fracture in an 81-year-old woman with new back pain who had undergone pelvic irradiation for vulvar cancer. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate symmetrically increased FDG avidity in the bilateral sacral ala (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image of the sacrum shows low-signal-intensity edema admixed with high-signal-intensity fat (arrowheads). The presence of fat is indicative of bone marrow, not tumor, in the patient’s sacral insufficiency fracture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig10b.jpeg" height="615" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Radiation-induced sacral insufficiency fracture in an 81-year-old woman with new back pain who had undergone pelvic irradiation for vulvar cancer. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate symmetrically increased FDG avidity in the bilateral sacral ala (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal T1-weighted MR image of the sacrum shows low-signal-intensity edema admixed with high-signal-intensity fat (arrowheads). The presence of fat is indicative of bone marrow, not tumor, in the patient’s sacral insufficiency fracture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig11a.jpeg" height="902" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Radiation-induced esophagitis in a 41-year-old woman who had undergone radiation therapy for mediastinal Hodgkin lymphoma. MIP FDG PET image <b>(a)</b> and sagittal CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images <b>(b)</b> demonstrate linear FDG avidity along the upper-to-mid thoracic esophagus (arrow), a finding that represents postradiation esophagitis. There was no evidence of FDG-avid lymphoma after treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig11b.jpeg" height="787" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Radiation-induced esophagitis in a 41-year-old woman who had undergone radiation therapy for mediastinal Hodgkin lymphoma. MIP FDG PET image <b>(a)</b> and sagittal CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images <b>(b)</b> demonstrate linear FDG avidity along the upper-to-mid thoracic esophagus (arrow), a finding that represents postradiation esophagitis. There was no evidence of FDG-avid lymphoma after treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig12a.jpeg" height="908" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Radiation hepatitis in a 67-year-old man who underwent chemotherapy and radiation therapy for a gastroesophageal junction adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> MIP FDG PET image <b>(a)</b> and axial fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> of the liver obtained after radiation therapy demonstrate a wedge-shaped area of increased FDG avidity in the anterior left hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a corresponding wedge-shaped region of low attenuation (arrow). These findings represent radiation hepatitis. In the axial fused PET/CT image, fiducial markers are seen at the gastroesophageal junction (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), indicating the site of the treated and now resolved gastroesophageal mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig12b.jpeg" height="688" width="923" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Radiation hepatitis in a 67-year-old man who underwent chemotherapy and radiation therapy for a gastroesophageal junction adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> MIP FDG PET image <b>(a)</b> and axial fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> of the liver obtained after radiation therapy demonstrate a wedge-shaped area of increased FDG avidity in the anterior left hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a corresponding wedge-shaped region of low attenuation (arrow). These findings represent radiation hepatitis. In the axial fused PET/CT image, fiducial markers are seen at the gastroesophageal junction (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), indicating the site of the treated and now resolved gastroesophageal mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig12c.jpeg" height="688" width="951" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Radiation hepatitis in a 67-year-old man who underwent chemotherapy and radiation therapy for a gastroesophageal junction adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> MIP FDG PET image <b>(a)</b> and axial fused PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> of the liver obtained after radiation therapy demonstrate a wedge-shaped area of increased FDG avidity in the anterior left hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a corresponding wedge-shaped region of low attenuation (arrow). These findings represent radiation hepatitis. In the axial fused PET/CT image, fiducial markers are seen at the gastroesophageal junction (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), indicating the site of the treated and now resolved gastroesophageal mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig13a.jpeg" height="761" width="1241" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Radiation injury to the left hypoglossal nerve with denervation of the left hemitongue in a 57-year-old woman who underwent irradiation for nasopharyngeal cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate an area of increased FDG uptake in the right hemitongue (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image of the tongue shows high signal intensity in the left hemitongue (arrow), with well-defined linear demarcation from the normal right hemitongue. The high T2 signal in the left hemitongue represents edema from denervation. The FDG avidity in the right hemitongue is increased as it attempts to compensate for the dysfunctional left hemitongue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig13b.jpeg" height="761" width="634" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Radiation injury to the left hypoglossal nerve with denervation of the left hemitongue in a 57-year-old woman who underwent irradiation for nasopharyngeal cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate an area of increased FDG uptake in the right hemitongue (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image of the tongue shows high signal intensity in the left hemitongue (arrow), with well-defined linear demarcation from the normal right hemitongue. The high T2 signal in the left hemitongue represents edema from denervation. The FDG avidity in the right hemitongue is increased as it attempts to compensate for the dysfunctional left hemitongue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig14a.jpeg" height="809" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Bone marrow and splenic repopulation in a 45-year-old man who received G-CSF after undergoing bone marrow transplantation. MIP FDG PET image <b>(a)</b> and axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images <b>(b)</b> demonstrate diffusely increased FDG uptake in the skeleton and in the spleen (arrowhead) to a lesser extent. In the context of recent G-CSF treatment, these findings are consistent with diffuse reactive marrow hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig14b.jpeg" height="635" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Bone marrow and splenic repopulation in a 45-year-old man who received G-CSF after undergoing bone marrow transplantation. MIP FDG PET image <b>(a)</b> and axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images <b>(b)</b> demonstrate diffusely increased FDG uptake in the skeleton and in the spleen (arrowhead) to a lesser extent. In the context of recent G-CSF treatment, these findings are consistent with diffuse reactive marrow hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig15a.jpeg" height="741" width="567" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Thymic hyperplasia in an 8-year-old boy who received a bone marrow transplant for Epstein-Barr virus lymphoproliferative disease. <b>(a, b)</b> MIP PET image <b>(a)</b> and axial fused PET/CT (top) and CT (bottom) images <b>(b)</b> from a pretransplantation staging examination demonstrate an FDG-avid anterior mediastinal mass (arrows), which proved to be lymphoproliferative disease. <b>(c, d)</b> After bone marrow transplantation, MIP PET image <b>(c)</b> and axial fused PET/CT (top) and CT (bottom) images <b>(d)</b> demonstrate FDG uptake in a triangular anterior mediastinal structure (arrows). The triangular shape of the normal thymus as it is molded by the adjacent lung parenchyma is consistent with benign thymic hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig15b.jpeg" height="1264" width="929" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Thymic hyperplasia in an 8-year-old boy who received a bone marrow transplant for Epstein-Barr virus lymphoproliferative disease. <b>(a, b)</b> MIP PET image <b>(a)</b> and axial fused PET/CT (top) and CT (bottom) images <b>(b)</b> from a pretransplantation staging examination demonstrate an FDG-avid anterior mediastinal mass (arrows), which proved to be lymphoproliferative disease. <b>(c, d)</b> After bone marrow transplantation, MIP PET image <b>(c)</b> and axial fused PET/CT (top) and CT (bottom) images <b>(d)</b> demonstrate FDG uptake in a triangular anterior mediastinal structure (arrows). The triangular shape of the normal thymus as it is molded by the adjacent lung parenchyma is consistent with benign thymic hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig15c.jpeg" height="741" width="658" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> Thymic hyperplasia in an 8-year-old boy who received a bone marrow transplant for Epstein-Barr virus lymphoproliferative disease. <b>(a, b)</b> MIP PET image <b>(a)</b> and axial fused PET/CT (top) and CT (bottom) images <b>(b)</b> from a pretransplantation staging examination demonstrate an FDG-avid anterior mediastinal mass (arrows), which proved to be lymphoproliferative disease. <b>(c, d)</b> After bone marrow transplantation, MIP PET image <b>(c)</b> and axial fused PET/CT (top) and CT (bottom) images <b>(d)</b> demonstrate FDG uptake in a triangular anterior mediastinal structure (arrows). The triangular shape of the normal thymus as it is molded by the adjacent lung parenchyma is consistent with benign thymic hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig15d.jpeg" height="1264" width="946" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span> Thymic hyperplasia in an 8-year-old boy who received a bone marrow transplant for Epstein-Barr virus lymphoproliferative disease. <b>(a, b)</b> MIP PET image <b>(a)</b> and axial fused PET/CT (top) and CT (bottom) images <b>(b)</b> from a pretransplantation staging examination demonstrate an FDG-avid anterior mediastinal mass (arrows), which proved to be lymphoproliferative disease. <b>(c, d)</b> After bone marrow transplantation, MIP PET image <b>(c)</b> and axial fused PET/CT (top) and CT (bottom) images <b>(d)</b> demonstrate FDG uptake in a triangular anterior mediastinal structure (arrows). The triangular shape of the normal thymus as it is molded by the adjacent lung parenchyma is consistent with benign thymic hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig16a.jpeg" height="789" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Bleomycin-induced pneumonitis in a 62-year-old man who received bleomycin for Hodgkin lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Posttreatment MIP PET image demonstrates multiple areas of focal FDG avidity in both lungs (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images show extensive areas of FDG-avid ground-glass attenuation (arrows). In the context of recent bleomycin chemotherapy, these findings are consistent with bleomycin-induced pneumonitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig16b.jpeg" height="725" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Bleomycin-induced pneumonitis in a 62-year-old man who received bleomycin for Hodgkin lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Posttreatment MIP PET image demonstrates multiple areas of focal FDG avidity in both lungs (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images show extensive areas of FDG-avid ground-glass attenuation (arrows). In the context of recent bleomycin chemotherapy, these findings are consistent with bleomycin-induced pneumonitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig17.jpeg" height="794" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Bisphosphonate-induced osteonecrosis of the jaw in a 64-year-old woman who received bisphosphonates for breast cancer with bone metastases. Coronal CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate new increased FDG avidity in the right side of the lower jaw (arrows). Prior osseous lesions were improving (not shown). In the context of recent bisphosphonate use, this finding is consistent with bisphosphonate-induced osteonecrosis of the jaw, which was proved at biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig18.jpeg" height="598" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Ipilimumab-induced enterocolitis in a 53-year-old woman who received ipilimumab for metastatic melanoma. Axial CT (left) and fused PET/CT (right) images demonstrate diffusely increased FDG uptake in the colon (arrows). In the context of recent anti-CTLA4 antibody ipilimumab immunotherapy, this finding is consistent with immune-mediated enterocolitis. A small FDG-avid soft-tissue nodule (arrowheads) in the left subcutaneous buttock represents active melanoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig19a.jpeg" height="717" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Vincristine pancreatitis in a 19-year-old man who received vincristine for T-cell lymphoblastic leukemia. <b>(a)</b> MIP PET image demonstrates FDG avidity (arrow) in the upper abdomen. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT (left) and CT (right) images show corresponding FDG-avid soft tissue adjacent to the pancreas (arrows). In the context of recent vincristine chemotherapy, the finding is consistent with vincristine-induced pancreatitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125105/asset/images/large/125105fig19b.jpeg" height="616" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Vincristine pancreatitis in a 19-year-old man who received vincristine for T-cell lymphoblastic leukemia. <b>(a)</b> MIP PET image demonstrates FDG avidity (arrow) in the upper abdomen. <b>(b)</b> Axial fused PET/CT (left) and CT (right) images show corresponding FDG-avid soft tissue adjacent to the pancreas (arrows). In the context of recent vincristine chemotherapy, the finding is consistent with vincristine-induced pancreatitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125105&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Bakheet SMB, Powe J, Kandil A, Ezzat A, Rostom A, Amartey J. F-18 FDG uptake in breast infection and inflammation. <em>Clin Nucl Med</em> 2000;25(2): 100–103.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/00003072-200002000-00003">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10656642/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=F-18+FDG+uptake+in+breast+infection+and+inflammation&amp;author=SMB+Bakheet&amp;author=J+Powe&amp;author=A+Kandil&amp;author=A+Ezzat&amp;author=A+Rostom&amp;author=J+Amartey&amp;publication_year=2000&amp;journal=Clin+Nucl+Med&amp;pages=100-103&amp;doi=10.1097%2F00003072-200002000-00003&amp;pmid=10656642">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Bhargava P, Zhuang H, Kumar R, Charron M, Alavi A. Iatrogenic artifacts on whole-body F-18 FDG PET imaging. <em>Clin Nucl Med</em> 2004;29(7):429–439.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/01.rlu.0000129124.52554.92">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15192468/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Iatrogenic+artifacts+on+whole-body+F-18+FDG+PET+imaging&amp;author=P+Bhargava&amp;author=H+Zhuang&amp;author=R+Kumar&amp;author=M+Charron&amp;author=A+Alavi&amp;publication_year=2004&amp;journal=Clin+Nucl+Med&amp;pages=429-439&amp;doi=10.1097%2F01.rlu.0000129124.52554.92&amp;pmid=15192468">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Belakhlef A, Jani C, Church C, Fraser R, Lakhanpal S. Fat necrosis mimicking B-cell lymphoma: a PET/CT and FDG study. <em>Clin Nucl Med</em> 2008;33(4): 271–272.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/RLU.0b013e3181662bbf">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18356666/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Fat+necrosis+mimicking+B-cell+lymphoma%3A+a+PET%2FCT+and+FDG+study&amp;author=A+Belakhlef&amp;author=C+Jani&amp;author=C+Church&amp;author=R+Fraser&amp;author=S+Lakhanpal&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=Clin+Nucl+Med&amp;pages=271-272&amp;doi=10.1097%2FRLU.0b013e3181662bbf&amp;pmid=18356666">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Seo YY, Yoo IR, Hyun OJ, Kim SH, Chung SK. FDG uptake in fat necrosis following transverse rectus abdominis myocutaneous (TRAM) flap reconstructed breasts: 3 cases. <em>Clin Nucl Med</em> 2010;35(4):283–285.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/RLU.0b013e3181d1905a">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20305426/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=FDG+uptake+in+fat+necrosis+following+transverse+rectus+abdominis+myocutaneous+%28TRAM%29+flap+reconstructed+breas